h3. *Problem Definition*

Due to a recent change done from Atlassian end, the customer username is now replaced with qm <codes> such as: 
{code:java}
qm:4c4abce8-4872-3fd6-844f-64f8c8dg5e9a:5acb246f2de58r2b3a943dbd {code}
Because of this when a customer is mentioned and chosen from the drop-down list, you will see the following: 

!example.png|width=632,height=167!

Customer would like to see the following option back in the comment section when mentioning user:
{code:java}
[~test.atlassian@atlassian.com] {code}
h3. *Why This is Important*

As of now this is not user-friendly and there is a possibility that you could include a wrong qm <code> and you will have to "preview" the comment everytime just to ensure you have the right customer mentioned. This can be confusing and lead to a lot of easy mistakes by mentioning the wrong customer. 

The customer understands that you can "preview" the mention made but this action was not necessary the last time, when the email address was shown, as it was direct and easy to understand.

*Summary*

 When SLA *Goals* JQL are set with the Organization field it can lead to irregular results based on how the quotes are utilized. The irregular results would usually lead to the SLA not being applied on an issue key even though the JQL gives the green tick on the SLA being configured. 

 

 

*Steps to Reproduce*
 # Go to the SLA page of the Service Desk Project
 # Create a new SLA and name it
 # Set an easy *Start* condition such as: *Issue Created*, the *Pause* and *Stop* conditions can be anything.
 # In the *Goal* section start creating a JQL such as the following: 

{code:java}

Organizations = "Test" {code}

 # The JQL will prompt you a "green tick" indicating the JQL is valid and you can *Update* and click on *Save* to apply the JQL
 # Create an issue to the Service Desk portal and ensure this customer is apart of the Organization Test. 
 # When the ticket is created the *Goal* will not be applied to the newly created ticket despite meeting the conditions. 

  

 

*Expected Results*

The *JQL* set in the Goal's JQL should be applied to the ticket that meets the condition for the *Organizations*. 

 

*Actual Results*

The *JQL* set in the Goal's JQL does not apply to the ticket that meets the condition for the *Organizations*. 

 

*Workaround:*
Despite giving you the "green tick" which indicates that the JQL is correct it in fact does not process the JQL that you have configured, there are a number of rules with the quote. 

*Scenario A: Organization Only JQL* 

**If the JQL only contains the Organization, remove the quotes and it will work. 


{code:java}
 Organizations = Test {code}
 

*Scenario B: Organization and Other Conditions JQL Version 1*

**If the JQL only contains the *Organization* and another condition, in this case if the *Organization* has quotes, ensure the second condition also has quotes, this applies to the third and so on condition, all of it must have quotes to work:

SUCCESS: 
{code:java}
Organizations = "Test" AND priority = "High"{code}
 FAILURE:
{code:java}
Organizations = "Test" AND priority = High{code}
 

*Scenario C: Organization and Other Conditions JQL Version 2*

**If the JQL only contains the *Organization* and another condition, in this case if the *Organization* does not have quotes, the second condition does not have to remove quotes, this applies to the third and so on condition:

SUCCESS: 
{code:java}
Organizations = Test AND priority = High{code}
 SUCCESS:
{code:java}
Organizations = Test AND priority = "High"{code}
 

*Note:*

**This issue does not occur with *Issue Navigator*, regardless of quote or no quote, the search result is accurate, only replicated so far in the SLA *Goal* JQL column.

